SIMPLE: sonorous
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sonorous
<hw>So*no"rous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>sonorus</ets>, fr. <ets>sonor</ets>, <ets>-oris</ets>, a sound,
akin to <ets>sonus</ets> a sound. See <er>Sound</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Giving sound when struck; resonant; <as>as, <ex>sonorous</ex>
metals</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Loud-sounding; giving a clear or loud sound; <as>as,
a <ex>sonorous</ex> voice</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Yielding sound; characterized by sound; vocal;
sonant; <as>as, the vowels are <ex>sonorous</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Impressive in sound; high-sounding.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Italian opera, amidst all the meanness and familiarty of the
thoughts, has something beautiful and <qex>sonorous</qex> in the
expression.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is nothing of the artificial Johnsonian balance in his
style. It is as often marked by a pregnant brevity as by a
<qex>sonorous</qex> amplitude.</q> <rj><qau>E. Everett.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Sonant; vibrant; hence, of sounds
produced in a cavity, deep-toned; <as>as, <ex>sonorous</ex>
rhonchi</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sonorous figures</b></col> <fld>(Physics)</fld>,
<cd>figures formed by the vibrations of a substance capable of emitting
a musical tone, as when the bow of a violin is drawn along the edge of a
piece of glass or metal on which sand is strewed, and the sand arranges
itself in figures according to the musical tone. Called also
<altname>acoustic figures</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Sonorous
tumor</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>a tumor which emits a clear,
resonant sound on percussion.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>So*no"rous*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>So*no"rous*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sonship</ent>⟦br⟧
